In response to attribution of recent climate change, the City of Melbourne, in 2002, set a target to reduce carbon emissions to net zero by 2020/21. Over the two decade period, Melbourne has already achieved a 40-50% reduction in emissions since 1990. Melbourne is also committed to achieving the global goal of limiting warming to 2°C. In addition to the reduction in global emissions associated with Melbourne, the City of Melbourne is committed to addressing other impacts of climate change. This means addressing climate change by:

Improving the quality of urban planning and infrastructure systems;

Increasing the availability of clean energy, transport and waste;

Developing and managing land use planning and development;

Reducing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions from waste generation and land use, including transportation;

Reducing energy intensity by reducing the cost of energy while increasing its renewable nature and use; and

Developing and implementing greenhouse gas tracking systems.

